58. ad. exemplar Epicharmi: Orelli justly says that it is very difficult to determine the exact meaning of this line, because we have not the means of comparing Plautus with Epicharmus, of whose comedies we have few considerable fragments preserved. He thinks that properare=ad eventum festinare (A. P. 148), and that it refers to the rapid progress of the action of the plays. So too Teuffel ἓ 97, 2. Schiitz understands it of rapidity of produc- tion. Mahaffy says that it seems only to apply to the easy flow of the dialogue’ (G7eek Lit. 1, p. 403); but Sellar is more nearly right in extending it to‘ the extreme vivacity and rapidity of gesture, dialogue‚ declamation and recitative, by which his scenes were characterised’ (Roman Poets, p. 194).
